model_explanation: S1 says Rob was the only recipient of bananas, so if Tom didn’t receive bananas, that’s consistent, but the focus on Rob (“only ROB”) contrasts with possible other recipients like Tom. Thus, S2 is independently true but not required directly by S1.

S1 emphasizes that Tom only received grapes, so indicating he received no oranges (as in S2) reinforces the restriction in S1. But S2 is more specific than necessary to infer from S1, so it’s not strictly entailed.
S1 says Sue received only oranges, but S2 contradicts that by saying she also got apples. Hence, these statements directly contradict each other.
S1 speaks about Sue being the only recipient of bananas, but S2 says something about what Rob didn’t receive. These statements don’t directly relate and can be considered independent.
if Tom only got oranges, it necessarily entails that he didn’t get bananas. S2 is fully entailed by S1.
if Sue only received apples, it logically follows that she did not receive oranges. Thus, S2 is entailed by S1.
if Sue only received grapes, then it must be true that she didn’t get apples. Therefore, S2 is entailed by S1.
S1 claims that Ellen only got oranges, while S2 says she also got bananas. This creates a direct contradiction.
if Mary only received grapes, it necessarily follows that she didn't get apples. Thus, S2 is entailed by S1.
S1 is about what Bill received, while S2 is about Mary. These statements don’t directly relate to each other and are independent.
